<font color="#FF0000">MEDALS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Feb 25 19:05:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Doctor Spatz's references to us as being &quot;loyal fidos&quot; is merely the latest attempt by someone who wants to portray those who fought in Vietnam as baby killers or as something less than human. Dehumanizing us makes his life more acceptable. Don't waste your time listening to his talk that we are all brothers.<br><br>
Don't waste your time trying to explain things to Dr Spatz. He will never understand. He does not want to understand. Understanding on his part would require him to relinquish the imagined &quot;hold&quot; he has over Vietnam Veterans. <br><br>
He needs to hear from us that the war was wrong, the war was wrong, the war was wrong. Over and Over! Understanding on his part would mean that he would no longer need to hear this sweet refrain that reinforces the decision he made 30 years ago not to go to Vietnam. <br><br>
Amnesty was the worst thing to happen to Dr Spatz. He was no longer the martyr!<br><br>
I knew 2 Conscientious Objectors while I served in Vietnam. Both were Army medics. One was terribly wounded.<br><br>
The first story I ever posted in Usenet was about them. I received an e mail from Doc Joe Kralich the following day. He served 2 tours of duty as a CO medic. One was with the Americal Division during the bloodiest time of the war. I was honored to receive a congratulatory note from this man.<br><br>
Dr Spatz have you ever wondered what it was like? Combat? The awful confusion? the cry of &quot;incoming&quot; and the subsequent, dreaded cry for a medic? Did you ever wonder how you would react? Whether you could get up from your position after shitting in your britches to help a fellow soldier? Men like Frank Garcia, and Art Combs and Joe Kralich know.<br>
They didn't carry weapons either. They would laugh at someone like you who referred to them as loyal fidos that begged for treats. <br><br>
Medals may be an &quot;ego&quot; thing. To allow oneself to feel the slightest glimmer of realization that he had the &quot;right stuff&quot;. Ego. Could be.<br><br>
I'm sure that the rigid world of Dr Barry Spatz doesn't allow for an ego. But we all are coming to realize that <br>
your's is an altogether different world anyway.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


